        "\n",
        "# Presentation Guidelines\n",
        "\n",
        "Each team presents their **financial technology product** — a domain-scoped RAG system built on SEC 10-K filings for a specific NAICS 4-digit industry. You are presenting to a simulated audience of FinTech stakeholders: potential investors, product managers, or a regulatory analytics team.\n",
        "\n",
        "Each team gives a 10-12 minute presentation plus 3 minutes Q&A.\n",
        "\n",
        "Expected flow:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. NAICS industry selection and company scope — why this industry, who are the companies\n",
        "2. Data pipeline and metadata quality — what you collected and how reliable it is\n",
        "3. Item cleaning and EDA highlights — what patterns emerged in the corpus\n",
        "4. Retrieval and generation pipeline — how the product answers questions\n",
        "5. Evaluation results and failure cases — honest assessment of product performance\n",
        "6. Practical recommendations — what would the next sprint look like for this product\n",
        "\n",
        "## Recommended Slide Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "A strong AD698 project presentation should feel like a product walkthrough, not a notebook recap. One especially effective structure is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Title and product framing** — team, NAICS industry, target user, business problem\n",
        "2. **System architecture overview** — one pipeline diagram from filings to grounded answer\n",
        "3. **Data acquisition and section scoping** — which SEC Items were used and why\n",
        "4. **Cleaning, chunking, and corpus inspection** — chunking strategy, metadata, corpus scale, and quality checks\n",
        "5. **Embeddings and vector store** — model choice, index type, and why those choices fit the product\n",
        "6. **Retrieval and re-ranking** — how the system finds evidence and improves precision\n",
        "7. **Generation design** — prompt strategy, citation format, refusal behavior, and grounded answer logic\n",
        "8. **Query experiments** — representative industry questions and why those questions matter\n",
        "9. **Evaluation** — retrieval relevance, grounding, citation accuracy, hallucination risk, and refusal behavior\n",
        "10. **Failure cases and improvements** — honest limitations plus next-sprint fixes\n",
        "11. **Business recommendations** — what this system is useful for now, and what must improve before deployment\n",
        "\n",
        "This structure is strong because it moves from architecture to implementation to evidence to business value in a way non-technical stakeholders can follow.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Recommended Slide Design Pattern\n",
        "\n",
        "When possible, make each technical section answer two questions:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **What did we build?**\n",
        "- **Why does this design choice matter?**\n",
        "\n",
        "That pattern worked especially well in strong prior RAG presentations because it prevented the slides from becoming a code dump.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Required Evidence in Slides\n",
        "\n",
        "- at least one data quality table\n",
        "- at least one retrieval quality example\n",
        "- at least one grounded answer with citations\n",
        "- one evaluation summary chart\n",
        "- one explainability or provenance slide showing how the team audited the system\n",
        "- one architecture or pipeline overview slide\n",
        "\n",
        "## Recommended Explainability / Audit Slide\n",
        "\n",
        "Because this is a RAG product, the most defensible explainability evidence is usually provenance rather than a generic \"black box explanation.\" A strong slide can show one of the following:\n",
        "\n",
        "- retrieved chunks with similarity or reranker scores\n",
        "- answer text aligned to cited chunks\n",
        "- failure case with explanation of why retrieval or generation failed\n",
        "- SHAP/LIME/InterpretML output for an auxiliary classifier or market model, if the team built one\n",
        "\n",
        "If teams use SHAP, LIME, or Microsoft explainability tools, they must clearly say **what model** is being explained. These tools are appropriate for a classifier, ranker, or tabular market model; they should not be described as a complete explanation of the generative model itself.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Presentation Evidence Tips\n",
        "\n",
        "Strong prior project presentations also did a good job of using compact evidence blocks instead of dense text. Encourage teams to show:\n",
        "\n",
        "- a pipeline diagram instead of a paragraph of architecture description\n",
        "- a chunking or corpus table instead of only describing data quality verbally\n",
        "- one top-k retrieval example with scores and metadata\n",
        "- one grounded answer that visibly points back to cited chunks\n",
        "- one evaluation slide that separates `faithfulness` from `relevance`\n",
        "- one failure-analysis slide with `what happened`, `why it matters`, and `future fix`\n",
        "\n",
